<section id="about" class="about">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-label">Collection note</p>
    <div class="about-grid">
      <div class="about-text">
        <h2>A single car,<br /><em>carefully traced</em></h2>
        <p>
          This page follows one machine: Joe Petty&rsquo;s 1962 Lotus Super 7 (Series II),
          reconstructed from public USA7s posts. Joe is listed as a retired owner in
          Jacksonville, Florida, with documented activity from 2016 to 2025.
        </p>
        <p>
          Across those entries, the car appears as an ex-racer returned to regular use:
          wiring renewed, drivetrain and shifter details resolved, and period-correct parts
          sourced where possible. The emphasis is stewardship, not mythmaking.
        </p>
        <p>
          The model itself sits in an important window of Lotus history. The Seven line began in
          1957 under Colin Chapman&rsquo;s &ldquo;add lightness&rdquo; philosophy, and the Series II arrived in
          June 1960 with a more road-focused setup than Series I while keeping the same lightweight,
          front-engine/rear-drive character.
        </p>
        <p>
          For period-correct context, Super Seven S2 variants commonly used Ford Kent-family
          engines around 1340cc or 1499cc, with contemporary Cosworth-tuned variants offered in
          period and occasional later crossflow installations near the end of Series II production.
          This archive separates known owner evidence from broader factory-era references.
        </p>
        <p>
          Body construction in this era paired a light steel spaceframe with stressed alloy panels;
          period examples often mixed cycle or clamshell wing setups depending on trim and market.
          For this car specifically, the visible presentation is British racing green with yellow
          and chrome accents, echoing period club-racing character.
        </p>
        <p>
          When posts conflict, or describe earlier configurations, details are marked
          unverified until current specification can be confirmed.
        </p>
      </div>
